In .NET 10 (and Android 12+), `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` is fully deprecated at the OS level, so `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` no longer has any effect.

## Solution: Use `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`

MAUI now includes **`KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`** (enabled by default since .NET 8) which automatically scrolls/pads content when the keyboard opens. If it's not working for your layout, check these things:

### 1. Don't disable it accidentally

```csharp
// In MauiProgram.cs — do NOT add this line:
// Microsoft.Maui.Handlers.EditorHandler.Mapper.AppendToMapping("NoAutoScroll",
//     (h, v) => KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Disconnect(h));
```

### 2. Structure your layout for it to work

The input bar needs to be inside a layout that can be adjusted. A common pattern:

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <!-- Chat messages -->
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" ... />

    <!-- Input bar — this will be pushed up automatically -->
    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

### 3. If auto-scroll still doesn't work, use Android's `WindowInsets` API

In your `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;

protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);

    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window!.DecorView, new InsetsListener());
}

private class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

        // Apply bottom padding = max of keyboard or nav bar
        v.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom));

        return insets;
    }
}
```

### 4. For iOS — it usually just works

iOS `UIKit` handles keyboard avoidance natively. If you have issues, wrap your page content in a `ScrollView`.

---

**TL;DR:** Remove any `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust` calls, ensure `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` is not disconnected, and if needed, use the `WindowInsets` listener on Android for full control.
